<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01001j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01001j">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01001j"> 1(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> crimps</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;DEAD HORSE&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> They used to sign on, those old-time shell-backs, at the shipping master&apos;s office the day before sailing, and each claimed an advance of one month&apos;s pay. It was given them, not in cash, but in the form of an advance note, payable some days after the ship sailed. The shopkeepers and <mark>crimps</mark> of the shore cashed them at heavy discount, and&mdash;the last night ashore was a merry one. Not so the next morning. Running down channel, heavy-eyed and heavy-headed, the next port three or four months away, they went about their business gloomily, knowing that their pay for the first month was already gone &mdash; that for a month they would be working &ldquo;dead horse.&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> F.R. <small> <a name="DM23oct22" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DM23oct22"><cite title="source">Daily Mail</cite></a> (23 October 1922) 8/5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05092i" href="c05all.htm#c05092i">VI.C.05:092(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
